  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sustainable WASH intervention to disaster affected communities and IDPs in Hiran Region, Hirshabelle state of Somalia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">,AADSOM will improve access to safe water, sanitation facilities and promote good hygiene practices in an effort to improve the health conditions of the locations in Jalalaqsi district of Hiran region. Under this allocation, AADSOM will improve better access to clean water, use of latrines and increased health promotion and safe hygiene practices to 16,800 (4200 women, 2520 men, 5040 boys and 5040 girls) flood, conflict and AWD affected communities including internally displaced women, boys and girls. 
Lack of access to safe and adequate water and sanitation facilities coupled with poor hygiene knowledge practices puts these communities at risk to waterborne diseases and loss of life. AADSOM will target locations within Jalalaqsi district (please refer to the detailed list attached in the document tap). 
Key activities AADSOM would like to undertake within this project include: 
-Upgrade/Rehabilitation of one strategic borehole equipped through hybrid system, 13 strategic shallow wells with hand pumps capacity building of 8 WASH committees and 28 Well Operators to ensure continuity of service, operation and maintenance, coupled training on DDR and conflict resolution mechanisms as cross cutting
-Hygiene and sanitation promotion activities including construction of 178 gender separated IDP latrines with hand washing facilities and lockable doors to avoid GBV against women and girls 
-Conducting comprehensive hygiene promotion campaigns to reach 16,800 men, women, boys and girls through visiting house to house, schools, health centers and feeding centers 
-training 10 community hygiene promoters, who will carry out hygiene promotion activities during and after the project is faced out and 
-Distribution of 1000 HP kits to 1000 households (UNICEF will supply) with vulnerable populations served by the established water services. 
The proposed response took into consideration the impact of women, and children in terms of access to WASH services. It takes specific actions to prevent risk of gender-based violence against women/girls by consulting women the appropriate safe locations for the construction of the latrines and water sources to avoid walking women/girls long distance for searching water and their latrine needs.</narrative>
  </description>
